WEBVTT

00:00:01.280 --> 00:00:07.200
<v Speaker 1>Para this for para can also mean in order to.

00:00:07.200 --> 00:00:08.320
<v Speaker 1>In order to.

00:00:08.320 --> 00:00:11.040
<v Speaker 1>So in a sentence for example

00:00:11.620 --> 00:00:15.620
<v Speaker 1>We have spoken in order to resolve it.

00:00:15.620 --> 00:00:19.140
<v Speaker 1>We have spoken in order to resolve it.

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:23.540
<v Speaker 1>Now in English we could just say we have spoken to resolve it.

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:27.160
<v Speaker 1>No, we don't need to say in order to.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:36.040
<v Speaker 1>But whenever we have this to meaning in order to, we want to translate this as para in Spanish

00:00:36.220 --> 00:00:38.060
<v Speaker 1>So let's make this sentence.

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:41.100
<v Speaker 1>First bit is we have spoken.

00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:42.700
<v Speaker 1>We have spoken

00:00:43.940 --> 00:00:45.940
<v Speaker 2>Hemos hablado.

00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:47.620
<v Speaker 1>Hemos hablado.

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:49.060
<v Speaker 1>To resolve it.

00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:50.980
<v Speaker 1>In order to resolve it.

00:00:50.980 --> 00:00:54.500
<v Speaker 1>Now to resolve is resolver.

00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:56.740
<v Speaker 1>The same word, resolver.

00:00:56.740 --> 00:01:02.260
<v Speaker 1>So we have spoken in order to resolve it.

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:08.280
<v Speaker 2>Hemos hablado para resolverlo.

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:08.920
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:08.920 --> 00:01:12.200
<v Speaker 1>Hemos hablado para resolverlo.

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:13.160
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:13.020 --> 00:01:23.259
<v Speaker 1>So whilst the two of to resolve resolver would fit nicely here, I mean if we were to translate directly from English, we have spoken

00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:24.500
<v Speaker 1>to resolve it.

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:25.860
<v Speaker 1>It doesn't work in Spanish.

00:01:25.860 --> 00:01:30.100
<v Speaker 1>Whenever this to means in order to, we must put that para.

00:01:30.100 --> 00:01:33.380
<v Speaker 1>Hemos hablado para resolverlo.

00:01:33.380 --> 00:01:37.540
<v Speaker 1>You could say we have spoken in order to try to resolve it.

00:01:37.040 --> 00:01:40.720
<v Speaker 1>What was to try related to intention?

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:41.840
<v Speaker 1>Intentar.

00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:42.320
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:46.880
<v Speaker 1>We have spoken in order to try to resolve it.

00:01:47.860 --> 00:01:54.820
<v Speaker 2>Hemos hablado para intentar resolvar resolver

00:01:55.620 --> 00:01:56.500
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:56.500 --> 00:02:01.620
<v Speaker 1>Hemos hablado para intentar resolverlo.

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:02.980
<v Speaker 1>So only when the two

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:12.400
<v Speaker 1>implies in order to we want to put para the two forms of the verb in Spanish is not enough to include that meaning we must put para

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:19.240
<v Speaker 1>So for example, if you want to say I'm here to see you, does it mean I'm here in order to see you?

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:19.880
<v Speaker 1>Yes.

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:20.280
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:23.720
<v Speaker 1>So I am here to see you informally.

00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:28.580
<v Speaker 2>Estoy aquí para verte.

